%N A389991 Total number of descents in all heapable permutations of length n.
%C A389991 A permutation of [1..n] is heapable if it can be inserted, one element at a time, into a binary min-heap without violating the heap property.
%C A389991 A descent in a permutation p is an index i with 1<=i<=n-1 such that p(i)>p(i+1).
%C A389991 The number of descents is the count of such indices.
%H A389991 Benjamin Chen, Michael Cho, Mario Tutuncu-Macias, and Tony Tzolov, <a href="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.dam.2023.01.025">Efficient methods of calculating the number of heapable permutations</a>, Discrete Applied Mathematics Volume 331, 31 May 2023, Pages 126-137.
%H A389991 Manolopoulos Panagiotis, <a href="/A389991/a389991.py.txt">Python program</a>
%F A389991 a(n) = Sum_{k=1..n-1} k*A389487(n,k+1).
%e A389991 For n=4, the heapable permutations are:
%e A389991   (1,2,3,4): no descents  0.
%e A389991   (1,3,2,4): descent at (3,2)  1.
%e A389991   (1,2,4,3): descent at (4,3)  1.
%e A389991   (1,4,2,3): descent at (4,2)  1.
%e A389991   (1,3,4,2): descent at (4,2)  1.
%e A389991 So the total number of descents across all 5 heapable permutations of length 4 is: 0+1+1+1+1=4.
